ye clan of the Serer people, of unexplained etymology. This surname is also found among the Lebou people. Compare   Fye   3 and   Paye   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Faille","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Agathe, Andre.","Altered form of French   Faye  . Compare   Fayette   1 and   Foy   5.","French: metonymic occupational name for a torchbearer, from Old French <i>faille</i> ‘torch’ (from Late Latin <i>facilla</i>)."]},{"name":"Fay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, John Patrick, Donovan, Fergus, Kieran, Liam, Nuala.","English: nickname for a person believed to have supernatural qualities, from Middle English, Old French <i>faie</i> ‘fairy, witch’ (from Late Latin <i>fata</i> ‘fate, destiny’).","English: nickname for a trustworthy person, from Middle English, Old French <i>fei</i> ‘loyalty, trust’."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph de Faye was born about 1133, in Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France, his father, Raoul de Châtellerault, was 25 and his mother, Elisabeth de Faye-la-Vineuse et de Montsoreau, was 19. He married Adélaïde d'Aquitaine II. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1154, in Bromley, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 23."},"et":{"Abt 1133–Abt 1154":"umbes 1133–umbes 1154","1133–1154":"1133–1154","1145–1187":"1145–1187","115